title: Balzac Memorial Statue
description: Monument to Balzac is a sculpture by Auguste Rodin in memory of the French novelist Balzac. According to Rodin, the sculpture aims to portray the writer’s persona rather than a physical likeness.[1] The work was commissioned in 1891 by the Société des Gens de Lettres, a full size plaster model was displayed in 1898 at a Salon in Champ de Mars.[2] After coming under criticism the model was rejected by the société and Rodin moved it to his home in Meudon.[2] On July 2, 1939 (22 years after the sculptor's death) the model was cast in bronze for the first time and placed on the Boulevard du Montparnasse.

title: Fontaine de Léda
description: La fontaine de Léda (autrefois appelée fontaine de la rue de Vaugirard1, ou fontaine du Regard) est une fontaine parisienne datée de 1807 qui a subi un déplacement. En 1856, lors du percement de la rue de Rennes dans le cadre des travaux d'Haussmann, la fontaine fut démontée. Donnée au Sénat par le préfet de la Seine, elle fut remontée entre les contreforts placés à l'arrière de la fontaine Médicis.

urlhtml: Denys Puech's Monument renfermant les cendres de Francis Garnier
title: Denys Puech's Monument renfermant les cendres de Francis Garnier
description:
Denys Puech's Monument renfermant les cendres de Francis Garnier (Monument-enclosure for the ashes of Francis Garnier) was originally sculpted in 1898. 

Marie Joseph François (Francis) Garnier (1835 - 1873) was a French naval officer, colonial administrator, and explorer known for his expediations along the Mekong River in Southeast Asia. He was slain in a fight with the Black Flags in Hanoi, causing the french to abandon the city after a treaty with the Vietnamese. 

In 1983, Garnier's body was exhumed from its burial in Vietnam and incinerated. Along with the remains of Doudart de Lagrée, it was transported back to France and placed within the base of this monument in 1987.
